<body>
  <h1>Azentix Enterprise Interview Questions and Answers</h1>
  <p class="meta">Prepared for project-specific interview readiness. Date: April 22, 2026</p>

  <h2>1) Architecture and Fundamentals</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q1. What business problem does Azentix solve?</div><div class="a">A1. It gives operations teams one AI interface to orchestrate tasks across SAP, Salesforce, ServiceNow, Stripe, and HubSpot, replacing fragmented manual workflows and reducing response time.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q2. Why does this project use both .NET and Python?</div><div class="a">A2. .NET hosts the API, MCP interface, and director logic, while Python LangGraph workers handle queue-driven workflow automation. This split keeps API orchestration separate from event processing.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q3. Why is a gateway (Kong) used?</div><div class="a">A3. Kong centralizes ingress controls such as API key validation, rate limiting, CORS, and route management before requests reach the host service.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q4. What is the value of deterministic flows here?</div><div class="a">A4. Deterministic flows provide predictable execution for high-risk tasks like price updates and incident triage, lowering hallucination risk and supporting auditability.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q5. Where is LLM reasoning still useful in this design?</div><div class="a">A5. LLM reasoning is used for classification, decision support, and dynamic analysis where fixed rules are insufficient, but bounded by guardrails and validation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q6. What are the three primary use-case flows?</div><div class="a">A6. SAP to Salesforce price sync, ServiceNow incident triage, and Stripe billing alert handling with downstream ticketing and CRM updates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q7. Why use queue-based processing?</div><div class="a">A7. Queues decouple producers and consumers, smooth traffic spikes, and improve reliability for asynchronous enterprise events.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q8. Why separate queues by domain?</div><div class="a">A8. It isolates failures, allows independent scaling, and supports focused monitoring for each workflow type.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q9. What is MCP in this project?</div><div class="a">A9. MCP is the Model Context Protocol endpoint allowing compatible AI clients to discover tools and invoke them through JSON-RPC.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q10. Why expose both REST and MCP?</div><div class="a">A10. REST supports standard app integrations and UI calls, while MCP supports AI-native clients and tool interoperability.</div></div>

  <h2>2) ASP.NET Host, DI, and Runtime Configuration</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q11. How does model selection work?</div><div class="a">A11. The host reads MODEL_PROVIDER and required environment variables, then configures Azure OpenAI or Ollama services in DI.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q12. What happens if Azure is selected but Azure settings are missing?</div><div class="a">A12. Startup throws an InvalidOperationException to fail fast on invalid runtime configuration.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q13. Why register Kernel as singleton?</div><div class="a">A13. It avoids repeated heavy initialization, keeps plugin registrations consistent, and reduces overhead for frequent requests.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q14. Why are integration configs registered as singletons?</div><div class="a">A14. They represent immutable runtime configuration and are reused across plugins and services.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q15. What is the purpose of AddHttpClient in both app and kernel DI?</div><div class="a">A15. It ensures HttpClientFactory is available at host level and inside plugin-resolved dependencies, preventing direct socket-misuse patterns.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q16. How is RAG enablement decided?</div><div class="a">A16. RAG is enabled only when an embedding deployment/model is configured; otherwise NoOpRagAgent is used.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q17. Why is health check minimal in current code?</div><div class="a">A17. Current health check reports provider readiness, but it can be expanded for dependencies like RabbitMQ and external connectors.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q18. Why redirect root to chat.html?</div><div class="a">A18. It provides a direct user entry point to the UI and improves local/deployed usability.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q19. Why restrict Swagger to dev/staging?</div><div class="a">A19. To reduce production attack surface and avoid exposing interactive docs in sensitive environments.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q20. Why normalize ServiceNow URL?</div><div class="a">A20. It removes path/noise and keeps a stable instance base URL for API calls.</div></div>

  <h2>3) Security</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q21. How does app-level API key auth work?</div><div class="a">A21. Middleware checks X-API-Key for protected paths when INTERNAL_API_KEY is configured.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q22. Why constant-time compare for API keys?</div><div class="a">A22. To mitigate timing attacks that can infer secret values from comparison duration differences.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q23. Which routes are public by design?</div><div class="a">A23. Root, health, dashboard, and some static/documentation prefixes are public to support UX and diagnostics.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q24. Is allowing requests when INTERNAL_API_KEY is empty safe?</div><div class="a">A24. It is acceptable only in controlled dev/internal setups. Production should always set the key and enforce gateway controls.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q25. How is Stripe webhook authenticity verified?</div><div class="a">A25. WebhookController uses Stripe signature verification with STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET and rejects invalid signatures.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q26. Why fail closed when Stripe secret is missing?</div><div class="a">A26. It prevents accepting unverified events and blocks accidental insecure operation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q27. What additional security controls would you add?</div><div class="a">A27. RBAC by tenant, secret rotation automation, replay protection, per-tool authorization, and structured audit signing.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q28. How are credentials protected from model output leakage?</div><div class="a">A28. The system prompt forbids exposing credentials, and integrations should avoid logging sensitive values.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q29. What is the trust boundary sequence?</div><div class="a">A29. Client to gateway, gateway to host, host to plugins, plugins to external systems, and worker queue boundaries.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q30. How do you improve webhook replay protection?</div><div class="a">A30. Cache processed event IDs with TTL and reject duplicates after signature verification.</div></div>

  <h2>4) Director Agent and Guardrails</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q31. What is DirectorAgent responsible for?</div><div class="a">A31. It orchestrates task execution, chooses deterministic routes for known tasks, and runs a guarded ReAct loop for others.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q32. Why prevalidation before execution?</div><div class="a">A32. To block invalid IDs, placeholder configs, or missing prerequisites before expensive or risky operations occur.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q33. How are HumanReviewRequired cases triggered?</div><div class="a">A33. Through rule checks, low-confidence logic, invalid inputs, or policy signals in final output.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q34. Why does incident triage require RAG?</div><div class="a">A34. Triage quality depends on KB context retrieval; without retrieval, automation can be unsafe and is forced to review.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q35. What stops the model from skipping tool calls?</div><div class="a">A35. The loop verifies action and observation presence and blocks final answers if required tool evidence is missing.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q36. Why cap iterations and tokens?</div><div class="a">A36. To limit cost and avoid infinite loops while preserving response predictability.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q37. How are content filter blocks handled?</div><div class="a">A37. The agent retries once with sanitized context, then escalates to HumanReviewRequired if still blocked.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q38. What is stored in the audit trail?</div><div class="a">A38. Iteration number, timestamp, thought, action, observation result, and token usage metadata.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q39. How is final status inferred?</div><div class="a">A39. Combined response text is scanned for review signals; otherwise normal completion is used.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q40. Why deterministic executors for the three main task types?</div><div class="a">A40. They reduce uncertainty for critical enterprise writes and produce consistent, auditable execution paths.</div></div>

  <h2>5) LangGraph Worker and Queue Processing</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q41. What does worker.py do?</div><div class="a">A41. It loads config, compiles three LangGraph apps, and starts one consumer thread per queue.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q42. Why use daemon threads?</div><div class="a">A42. They simplify long-running worker behavior and allow process shutdown without orphaning custom thread management.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q43. Why set basic_qos(prefetch_count=1)?</div><div class="a">A43. It prevents one worker from taking too many unacked messages and improves fairness and backpressure handling.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q44. Why nack with requeue false on processing exceptions?</div><div class="a">A44. To avoid poison-message infinite loops. Failed messages should be investigated via DLQ or failure logging path.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q45. How does reconnection happen?</div><div class="a">A45. Consumer loop catches exceptions, logs, closes connection safely, and restarts loop.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q46. Why initialize explicit workflow state fields?</div><div class="a">A46. Typed explicit state improves node contract clarity and reduces runtime key errors.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q47. How does price sync route after analysis?</div><div class="a">A47. If no sync required, notify only. If sync required and approval needed, queue approval. Else auto-sync and notify.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q48. How does incident triage route?</div><div class="a">A48. It auto-resolves only when auto_resolvable is true and confidence is at least 0.8; otherwise it escalates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q49. Why include audit entries per node?</div><div class="a">A49. They support traceability, debugging, and post-incident reviews.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q50. What production upgrade is recommended for failed messages?</div><div class="a">A50. Add dead-letter exchanges and retry policies with capped attempts and structured failure metadata.</div></div>

  <h2>6) Flow-Specific Questions</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q51. How does SAP to Salesforce price sync begin?</div><div class="a">A51. Validate input IDs, fetch SAP price, fetch Salesforce pricebook entry, pull policy context, analyze discrepancy, then sync or queue approval.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q52. Why include RAG rules in price sync analysis?</div><div class="a">A52. It grounds decisions in policy thresholds and governance rules instead of relying only on model intuition.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q53. What triggers approval queue in price sync?</div><div class="a">A53. Rules-based analysis indicating discrepancy beyond auto-approval thresholds.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q54. What does auto_sync update in Salesforce?</div><div class="a">A54. UnitPrice and custom tracking fields such as sync reference and sync marker.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q55. What does incident triage fetch before classification?</div><div class="a">A55. Incident details from ServiceNow and matching KB articles for context.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q56. What is the triage confidence threshold for auto resolution?</div><div class="a">A56. 0.8 in current flow logic.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q57. What does stripe billing flow do after validating event type?</div><div class="a">A57. Fetch payment details, fetch customer, create ServiceNow incident, flag Salesforce opportunity, update HubSpot contact, then notify.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q58. Why is cross-system enrichment useful in billing failures?</div><div class="a">A58. It gives support and revenue teams complete context to act quickly and reduce churn.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q59. What is a risk of fallback mock values in integrations?</div><div class="a">A59. They can mask real outages if not environment-gated and clearly flagged in logs/alerts.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q60. How do you harden flow idempotency?</div><div class="a">A60. Use stable event IDs, dedupe stores, and conditional updates in downstream systems.</div></div>

  <h2>7) MCP and Tooling</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q61. What methods does MCP dispatch currently support?</div><div class="a">A61. initialize, tools/list, tools/call, and ping.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q62. What does tools/list return?</div><div class="a">A62. Static platform tools plus dynamically discovered Semantic Kernel plugin functions translated into MCP schemas.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q63. How are MCP tools mapped to agent tasks?</div><div class="a">A63. The controller maps tool names to taskType and description then calls DirectorAgent with input arguments.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q64. Why include SSE stream endpoint?</div><div class="a">A64. It enables clients to receive asynchronous progress and completion events without polling.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q65. What is a limitation of dynamic plugin exposure?</div><div class="a">A65. It can expose more operations than desired unless explicit allow-lists and policy checks are added.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q66. How would you secure MCP for external client access?</div><div class="a">A66. Add client identity, scoped auth tokens, per-tool authorization, and rate limits at gateway and app layers.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q67. Why keep JSON-RPC error structures standardized?</div><div class="a">A67. It ensures clients can reliably parse and react to failures across tools and methods.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q68. How would you version MCP tool contracts?</div><div class="a">A68. Use explicit version fields and compatibility windows with deprecation notices.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q69. What is a practical MCP test strategy?</div><div class="a">A69. Contract tests for initialize/list/call, schema validation tests, and end-to-end tool invocation tests with mocked integrations.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q70. How do you debug unknown tool failures quickly?</div><div class="a">A70. Capture request id, tool name, mapped task type, input schema snapshot, and director audit trail in structured logs.</div></div>

  <h2>8) Data, Memory, and RAG</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q71. What does SupabaseVectorMemory provide?</div><div class="a">A71. It stores embeddings and content in PostgreSQL/pgvector and supports similarity-based retrieval for context grounding.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q72. Why guard startup on missing DB connection?</div><div class="a">A72. To keep core service available even when vector storage is unavailable, while logging degraded mode.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q73. How does SearchAsync filter relevance?</div><div class="a">A73. It computes cosine-distance derived similarity and applies minRelevance with top-K ordering.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q74. How do you improve retrieval quality?</div><div class="a">A74. Better chunking, cleaner metadata filters, tuned thresholds, and regular evaluation against labeled queries.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q75. How do you support tenant isolation in memory?</div><div class="a">A75. Add tenant_id partition/filter in storage schema and enforce it at every save and search call.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q76. What risk exists if collections are mixed across domains?</div><div class="a">A76. Retrieval contamination can surface wrong policies, causing bad automation decisions.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q77. How do you prevent stale policy usage?</div><div class="a">A77. Include versioned policy metadata and freshness checks before using retrieved context.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q78. Why use pgvector rather than external vector DB here?</div><div class="a">A78. It simplifies operations by colocating vector data with relational metadata in one managed platform.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q79. What should be logged for retrieval diagnostics?</div><div class="a">A79. Query intent, topK, threshold, result IDs, scores, and final selected context snippets.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q80. How do you evaluate RAG regressions?</div><div class="a">A80. Run offline retrieval benchmarks and incident simulation scenarios before promoting embedding/prompt changes.</div></div>

  <h2>9) Testing, Reliability, and Observability</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q81. What unit tests are present in this repo?</div><div class="a">A81. Model defaults and rules tests, including placeholder detection and status inference checks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q82. What key tests are still missing?</div><div class="a">A82. End-to-end queue flow tests, webhook replay/idempotency tests, and MCP contract tests.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q83. How would you test external integrations safely?</div><div class="a">A83. Use provider sandboxes and HTTP mocks with contract snapshots for each connector.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q84. How would you test poison-message handling?</div><div class="a">A84. Inject malformed payloads and verify nack behavior, failure logs, and DLQ routing.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q85. What observability signals matter most?</div><div class="a">A85. Queue lag, processing latency, success/failure rates per flow, tool-call errors, and human-review rates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q86. Why track HumanReviewRequired as a KPI?</div><div class="a">A86. It measures automation quality and data readiness; spikes indicate policy/model/config issues.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q87. How would you correlate events across services?</div><div class="a">A87. Propagate a correlation ID from ingress through queue messages, logs, and downstream update payloads.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q88. How do you reduce duplicate processing on retries?</div><div class="a">A88. Enforce idempotency keys and upsert semantics in outbound writes.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q89. What reliability pattern is recommended for transient failures?</div><div class="a">A89. Retry with exponential backoff, timeout budgets, and circuit-breaker style degradation where appropriate.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q90. How would you monitor model cost and token usage?</div><div class="a">A90. Emit per-task token/latency metrics and aggregate by task type, model, and environment.</div></div>

  <h2>10) DevOps and Deployment</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q91. What deployment options are used?</div><div class="a">A91. Local run, Docker Compose, and Render blueprint deployment for host plus worker.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q92. Why split API and worker into separate services in deployment?</div><div class="a">A92. They have different scaling profiles and failure characteristics, so separate services improve operational control.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q93. Which environment variables are critical at runtime?</div><div class="a">A93. Model settings, integration credentials, webhook secret, API keys, and queue connection/queue names.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q94. How would you handle secret management in production?</div><div class="a">A94. Use a managed secret store and inject at runtime, with rotation and access policies.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q95. What readiness checks would you add beyond current health endpoint?</div><div class="a">A95. RabbitMQ connectivity, critical integration credential presence, and optional model endpoint probe checks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q96. How would you roll out risky flow changes?</div><div class="a">A96. Feature flags, canary traffic, and side-by-side evaluation with rollback guardrails.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q97. What is the main scaling bottleneck likely to appear first?</div><div class="a">A97. Queue consumer throughput and downstream API rate limits, not usually raw API server CPU.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q98. How do you approach DR for this architecture?</div><div class="a">A98. Backup queue topology/config, persist critical state, and automate environment recreation from infra and config templates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q99. What SLOs would you define?</div><div class="a">A99. API availability, queue processing latency percentiles, incident triage completion time, and failure/error budget targets.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q100. How do you control costs without hurting quality?</div><div class="a">A100. Prefer deterministic logic where possible, use smaller models for bounded tasks, optimize prompts/context, and monitor token spend by use case.</div></div>

  <h2>11) Scenario-Based Interview Questions with Model Answers</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q101. Stripe webhook traffic spikes 10x. What do you do first?</div><div class="a">A101. Check queue depth and consumer lag, scale worker consumers, enforce idempotency, and confirm downstream rate limits to avoid cascading failures.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q102. ServiceNow is down. How should the system behave?</div><div class="a">A102. Capture and queue intent safely, mark status for retry/review, avoid silent drops, and alert operations with degraded-mode signals.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q103. Salesforce update succeeds but HubSpot fails. How do you recover?</div><div class="a">A103. Emit compensating task/retry with correlation ID, record partial completion state, and provide operator visibility for reconciliation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q104. False auto-resolutions increase after model change. Next step?</div><div class="a">A104. Roll back model or threshold configuration, raise confidence threshold, and route more cases to human review until evaluation stabilizes.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q105. MCP client sends malformed payloads repeatedly. What do you implement?</div><div class="a">A105. Strict schema validation, explicit JSON-RPC errors, per-client rate limits, and security monitoring for abuse patterns.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q106. Tenant A monopolizes processing. How do you enforce fairness?</div><div class="a">A106. Partition queues or apply weighted scheduling and quotas per tenant, with separate consumption controls.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q107. Security asks for non-repudiation of agent actions. What do you add?</div><div class="a">A107. Signed structured audit events, immutable log sink, request identity propagation, and verified action receipts.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q108. RAG retrieves irrelevant policies. How do you fix?</div><div class="a">A108. Tighten metadata filters, improve chunk quality, tune threshold/topK, and benchmark with labeled policy retrieval tests.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q109. Leadership asks for lower inference cost. What is your plan?</div><div class="a">A109. Increase deterministic routing coverage, reduce prompt/context size, downgrade model for low-risk tasks, and track quality regression metrics.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q110. You must explain this system in two minutes in an interview. How do you summarize?</div><div class="a">A110. Azentix is a hybrid AI operations platform: secure .NET control plane plus queue-driven Python flows, deterministic for critical actions, LLM-guided where adaptive reasoning is needed, with auditability and human-review safeguards.</div></div>

  <h2>12) Quick Revision Prompts</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Prompt 1</div><div class="a">Explain the end-to-end path from Stripe webhook to ServiceNow ticket and CRM updates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Prompt 2</div><div class="a">Defend deterministic orchestration choices versus pure agentic behavior.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Prompt 3</div><div class="a">Describe guardrails used to prevent unsafe automation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Prompt 4</div><div class="a">Describe queue reliability strategy and poison-message handling.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Prompt 5</div><div class="a">Describe how MCP enables AI client interoperability in this system.</div></div>

  <h2>13) General Generative AI Interview Questions and Answers (Expanded)</h2>
  <p class="meta">Note: Public LinkedIn pages were partially accessible in this environment, while many pages are login-limited. This section adds comprehensive market-standard GenAI interview coverage on top of the existing Azentix-specific set.</p>

  <h2>14) GenAI Fundamentals (Q111-Q130)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q111. What is Generative AI?</div><div class="a">A111. Generative AI is a class of models that learns patterns from data and creates new content such as text, code, images, audio, or structured outputs.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q112. How is GenAI different from traditional discriminative AI?</div><div class="a">A112. Discriminative models classify or predict labels, while generative models model data distributions and generate new samples.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q113. What is an LLM?</div><div class="a">A113. A Large Language Model is a transformer-based model trained on large text corpora to predict tokens and perform language tasks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q114. Why do transformers dominate modern GenAI?</div><div class="a">A114. Self-attention captures long-range dependencies efficiently and scales well with data and compute.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q115. What is a token in LLM systems?</div><div class="a">A115. A token is a model-specific text unit (word piece/subword) used for input/output and cost accounting.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q116. What is context window?</div><div class="a">A116. It is the maximum number of tokens a model can process at once, including prompt and generated output.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q117. What is pretraining?</div><div class="a">A117. Pretraining is large-scale unsupervised/self-supervised learning where models learn language structure and world patterns.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q118. What is instruction tuning?</div><div class="a">A118. Fine-tuning on instruction-following datasets so the model responds better to user tasks and formats.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q119. What is RLHF?</div><div class="a">A119. Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback aligns model behavior with human preference rankings.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q120. What is hallucination in LLMs?</div><div class="a">A120. Hallucination is fluent but incorrect or unsupported output not grounded in reliable evidence.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q121. Why do hallucinations happen?</div><div class="a">A121. Next-token prediction optimizes plausibility, not truth; weak grounding and ambiguous prompts increase risk.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q122. What is zero-shot prompting?</div><div class="a">A122. Asking the model to perform a task without examples in the prompt.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q123. What is few-shot prompting?</div><div class="a">A123. Providing input-output examples in prompt to steer behavior and improve consistency.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q124. What is temperature?</div><div class="a">A124. A sampling parameter controlling randomness; lower values are more deterministic, higher values more diverse.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q125. What is top-p sampling?</div><div class="a">A125. It samples from the smallest token set whose cumulative probability exceeds p, controlling diversity.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q126. What is prompt engineering?</div><div class="a">A126. Designing instructions, context, examples, and output constraints to optimize model behavior for a task.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q127. What is grounding?</div><div class="a">A127. Supplying trusted external context so responses are based on verifiable source content.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q128. What is retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)?</div><div class="a">A128. A pattern that retrieves relevant knowledge and injects it into prompts before generation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q129. What is model alignment?</div><div class="a">A129. Aligning outputs with human values, safety rules, policy requirements, and intended use.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q130. What is the key GenAI production mindset?</div><div class="a">A130. Treat LLMs as probabilistic components that require guardrails, evaluation, observability, and fallback paths.</div></div>

  <h2>15) LLM Architecture and Training (Q131-Q150)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q131. Explain self-attention in simple terms.</div><div class="a">A131. Each token computes weighted relevance to other tokens, enabling context-aware representation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q132. What is multi-head attention?</div><div class="a">A132. Parallel attention heads capture different relationships, then combine for richer context features.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q133. What are positional encodings?</div><div class="a">A133. Signals that add token order information so transformers can model sequence structure.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q134. What is next-token prediction objective?</div><div class="a">A134. The model learns to predict the next token distribution given previous tokens.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q135. What is perplexity?</div><div class="a">A135. A metric indicating uncertainty in token prediction; lower perplexity generally means better language modeling.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q136. What is quantization?</div><div class="a">A136. Reducing numeric precision of model weights/activations to save memory and speed inference.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q137. What is LoRA?</div><div class="a">A137. Low-Rank Adaptation fine-tunes small adapter matrices while freezing base model weights.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q138. What is PEFT?</div><div class="a">A138. Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning methods that adapt models with fewer trainable parameters.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q139. Full fine-tuning vs PEFT?</div><div class="a">A139. Full fine-tuning updates all parameters for maximum flexibility but high cost; PEFT is cheaper and faster with modest trade-offs.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q140. What is catastrophic forgetting?</div><div class="a">A140. Fine-tuning can degrade previously learned capabilities when new data distribution dominates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q141. Why does data curation matter in tuning?</div><div class="a">A141. Label quality, coverage, and diversity directly determine behavior, reliability, and bias profile.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q142. What is synthetic data in GenAI training?</div><div class="a">A142. Model-generated examples used to bootstrap or augment datasets, typically with human/automated filtering.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q143. What is DPO?</div><div class="a">A143. Direct Preference Optimization is a preference-learning method that avoids full RL pipelines.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q144. What is instruction hierarchy?</div><div class="a">A144. Priority ordering of system, developer, and user instructions, often enforced by policy and runtime design.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q145. What is model distillation?</div><div class="a">A145. Training a smaller student model to mimic a larger teacher model to reduce latency and cost.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q146. Why benchmark across tasks instead of one metric?</div><div class="a">A146. Single metrics hide weaknesses; real-world quality needs multi-dimensional evaluation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q147. What is inference-time scaling?</div><div class="a">A147. Improving outputs using better prompting, retrieval, reranking, tool use, and constrained decoding without retraining.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q148. What is speculative decoding?</div><div class="a">A148. A speed-up method where a draft model proposes tokens and a larger model verifies them.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q149. Why can smaller models still win in production?</div><div class="a">A149. Lower latency/cost and easier scaling often outperform larger models for bounded tasks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q150. What is the practical training trade-off?</div><div class="a">A150. Balance capability gains with compute budget, deployment constraints, and safety requirements.</div></div>

  <h2>16) Prompting, RAG, and Agents (Q151-Q175)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q151. What are strong prompt components?</div><div class="a">A151. Clear instructions, grounded context, examples, output schema, and failure behavior.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q152. Why specify output format explicitly?</div><div class="a">A152. Structured outputs are easier to validate, parse, test, and integrate into workflows.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q153. What is recency bias in prompting?</div><div class="a">A153. Models may overweight later prompt text, so key instructions are often repeated near the end.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q154. When use chain-of-thought style decomposition?</div><div class="a">A154. For complex tasks, decompose into explicit steps, but avoid exposing sensitive reasoning traces in production.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q155. What is retrieval chunking?</div><div class="a">A155. Splitting source documents into smaller semantically coherent pieces for better recall and precision.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q156. What chunk size strategy works best?</div><div class="a">A156. Task-specific tuning; start medium-sized chunks with overlap, then optimize via retrieval metrics.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q157. What is embedding drift?</div><div class="a">A157. Changes in embedding models can alter nearest-neighbor behavior and degrade retrieval consistency.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q158. What is reranking in RAG?</div><div class="a">A158. A second-stage model reorders retrieved candidates to maximize relevance before generation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q159. What is hybrid retrieval?</div><div class="a">A159. Combining lexical and vector search for stronger recall across exact terms and semantic similarity.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q160. Why include citations in answers?</div><div class="a">A160. Citations improve trust, auditability, and detectability of unsupported claims.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q161. What is a tool call in LLM apps?</div><div class="a">A161. Structured invocation of external functions/APIs so models can fetch data or perform actions.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q162. What is an AI agent?</div><div class="a">A162. A system that plans, reasons, and executes multi-step tasks using tools and memory under policy constraints.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q163. What is agent orchestration?</div><div class="a">A163. Managing planning loops, tool routing, retries, and state transitions for agent tasks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q164. What is single-agent vs multi-agent design?</div><div class="a">A164. Single-agent is simpler and cheaper; multi-agent can improve specialization but adds coordination complexity.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q165. Why enforce tool allow-lists?</div><div class="a">A165. To prevent unauthorized actions and reduce prompt-injection blast radius.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q166. What is agent memory?</div><div class="a">A166. Persisted short-term and long-term context used to personalize and continue workflows.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q167. What is a planning failure in agents?</div><div class="a">A167. The agent loops, chooses wrong tools, or produces invalid execution plans due to weak constraints.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q168. How do you bound agent loops?</div><div class="a">A168. Max iterations, token budgets, timeout ceilings, and explicit stop criteria.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q169. What is reflection or self-critique pattern?</div><div class="a">A169. A second-pass validation step where model checks answer quality against constraints.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q170. Why can deterministic workflows outperform free-form agents?</div><div class="a">A170. They are predictable, testable, compliant, and often cheaper for repetitive high-risk operations.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q171. What is function-calling reliability issue?</div><div class="a">A171. Models may emit malformed arguments or call wrong tools; schema validation is mandatory.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q172. What is prompt injection?</div><div class="a">A172. Malicious content attempts to override system instructions or exfiltrate secrets through model behavior.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q173. How defend against prompt injection?</div><div class="a">A173. Isolate untrusted input, enforce policy layers, tool permissions, output filtering, and contextual sanitization.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q174. What is retrieval poisoning?</div><div class="a">A174. Corrupted or malicious indexed content manipulates model outputs through grounded context.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q175. How reduce retrieval poisoning risk?</div><div class="a">A175. Source trust controls, document moderation, ACL trimming, provenance scoring, and content validation pipelines.</div></div>

  <h2>17) Evaluation and Metrics (Q176-Q195)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q176. Why is GenAI evaluation harder than classic ML?</div><div class="a">A176. Outputs are open-ended and subjective, so quality needs multiple automatic and human metrics.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q177. What are common GenAI evaluation dimensions?</div><div class="a">A177. Correctness, groundedness, relevance, completeness, safety, latency, and cost.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q178. What is groundedness metric?</div><div class="a">A178. Degree to which response claims are supported by provided source context.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q179. What is faithfulness in RAG?</div><div class="a">A179. Whether generated answer stays faithful to retrieved evidence without unsupported additions.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q180. What is exact match and when is it weak?</div><div class="a">A180. Exact string equality; weak for paraphrasable tasks where semantically correct variants differ.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q181. BLEU/ROUGE in GenAI interviews?</div><div class="a">A181. Useful for some summarization/translation baselines but often insufficient for modern dialog quality.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q182. What is LLM-as-judge?</div><div class="a">A182. Using a model evaluator to score outputs against rubric, often with calibration against human labels.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q183. How avoid evaluator bias?</div><div class="a">A183. Use blind pairwise comparisons, multiple judges, and anchor with human-reviewed gold sets.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q184. What is win-rate evaluation?</div><div class="a">A184. A/B comparing two systems where evaluators choose preferred outputs across a query set.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q185. What is retrieval evaluation metric for search stage?</div><div class="a">A185. Recall@K, MRR, nDCG, and citation coverage are common for measuring retrieval quality.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q186. What is latency SLO for chat UX?</div><div class="a">A186. Common targets are first token in under 1-2 seconds and full response in a few seconds.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q187. Why track cost per successful task?</div><div class="a">A187. It ties spend to business outcome and exposes expensive low-value prompts or models.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q188. What is regression testing in GenAI?</div><div class="a">A188. Re-running fixed prompt/test suites after changes to detect quality, safety, or cost regressions.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q189. What is red teaming for GenAI?</div><div class="a">A189. Adversarial testing for jailbreaks, prompt injection, toxic outputs, and policy violations.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q190. How do you evaluate tool-calling quality?</div><div class="a">A190. Measure tool selection accuracy, argument validity, execution success, and task completion rate.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q191. What is uncertainty handling strategy?</div><div class="a">A191. Ask clarifying questions, abstain, or escalate to human when confidence is low.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q192. What is online evaluation?</div><div class="a">A192. Production A/B monitoring with user feedback and outcome telemetry.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q193. What is offline evaluation?</div><div class="a">A193. Benchmarks on curated test sets before release to validate quality and safety gates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q194. Why stratify test sets?</div><div class="a">A194. To cover easy, edge, adversarial, and domain-specific cases instead of overfitting to simple prompts.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q195. What is a strong GenAI release gate?</div><div class="a">A195. Minimum thresholds on quality, safety, latency, and cost, plus no critical policy regressions.</div></div>

  <h2>18) Responsible AI, Security, and Governance (Q196-Q215)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q196. What are core Responsible AI principles for GenAI?</div><div class="a">A196. Fairness, reliability, safety, privacy, transparency, accountability, and human oversight.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q197. What is PII risk in GenAI systems?</div><div class="a">A197. Sensitive data can be leaked through prompts, logs, retrieval indexes, or model outputs.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q198. How reduce PII exposure?</div><div class="a">A198. Data minimization, redaction, encryption, least privilege, and strict retention controls.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q199. What is jailbreak risk?</div><div class="a">A199. Attempts to bypass safety policies using prompt manipulation and instruction hijacking.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q200. What is policy enforcement stack in GenAI apps?</div><div class="a">A200. Input moderation, policy prompts, tool policy checks, output moderation, and audit logs.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q201. Why is human-in-the-loop critical?</div><div class="a">A201. High-impact tasks require human review for safety, compliance, and accountability.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q202. What is model card usage in interviews?</div><div class="a">A202. Model cards document capabilities, limitations, risks, and intended-use boundaries.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q203. What is data lineage in RAG?</div><div class="a">A203. Tracking source provenance from document ingestion to final response citations.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q204. Why enforce tenant isolation?</div><div class="a">A204. It prevents cross-tenant leakage in retrieval, memory, tool calls, and logs.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q205. What is governance for prompt/version changes?</div><div class="a">A205. Version control, approval workflow, change logs, staged rollout, and rollback policy.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q206. How do you audit GenAI actions?</div><div class="a">A206. Capture trace IDs, prompts, retrieval IDs, tool actions, outputs, and policy decisions with timestamps.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q207. What is over-automation risk?</div><div class="a">A207. Unsupervised high-confidence but wrong actions can cause business or compliance incidents.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q208. What is safe fallback strategy?</div><div class="a">A208. If confidence or policy checks fail, abstain, request clarification, or route to human.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q209. Why should prompts avoid secret material?</div><div class="a">A209. Prompt contents can appear in logs/telemetry or be exposed through debugging workflows.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q210. What is output filtering?</div><div class="a">A210. Applying safety/policy classifiers to generated content before user delivery.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q211. What is constitutional or policy-guided prompting?</div><div class="a">A211. Encoding behavioral rules that steer responses toward safe and compliant outcomes.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q212. What legal topics appear in GenAI interviews?</div><div class="a">A212. Copyright/IP, consented data usage, privacy regulations, and accountability for automated decisions.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q213. What is governance KPI to track monthly?</div><div class="a">A213. Safety violation rate, escalation rate, unresolved policy incidents, and audit completeness.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q214. How do you communicate model limitations to users?</div><div class="a">A214. Through transparent UX messaging, confidence cues, citations, and clear escalation paths.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q215. What is a good final governance principle?</div><div class="a">A215. High autonomy must always be matched by high observability, controls, and accountability.</div></div>

  <h2>19) GenAI System Design and Operations (Q216-Q240)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q216. Design a production GenAI assistant in one minute.</div><div class="a">A216. Use API gateway, auth, prompt orchestration, retrieval, tool layer, safety filters, tracing, and human fallback.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q217. What are major GenAI architecture layers?</div><div class="a">A217. Experience layer, orchestration layer, model layer, retrieval/data layer, and governance/observability layer.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q218. What is first-token latency and why care?</div><div class="a">A218. Time until streaming begins; it strongly affects user-perceived responsiveness.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q219. How reduce latency in RAG pipelines?</div><div class="a">A219. Parallel retrieval, caching, smaller prompts, optimized top-k, and faster/cheaper model for routing steps.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q220. What is semantic cache?</div><div class="a">A220. Cache keyed by embedding similarity so semantically similar queries reuse prior high-quality responses.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q221. What is prompt cache?</div><div class="a">A221. Reuse previously computed outputs for identical prompt templates and context hashes.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q222. Why use model routing?</div><div class="a">A222. Route simple tasks to cheaper models and complex tasks to stronger models for better cost-quality balance.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q223. What is cost control strategy?</div><div class="a">A223. Token budgets, truncation policies, model routing, caching, and deterministic workflows.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q224. What is observability stack for GenAI?</div><div class="a">A224. Prompt/response traces, retrieval metrics, tool telemetry, policy events, and business outcome signals.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q225. Why store prompt versions with traces?</div><div class="a">A225. It enables reproducibility and root-cause analysis after behavior changes.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q226. What is canary release for prompts/models?</div><div class="a">A226. Roll out to a small traffic slice, compare KPIs, then expand only if quality and safety pass.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q227. What is fallback hierarchy?</div><div class="a">A227. Primary model, backup model, deterministic rules, then human escalation.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q228. How to handle tool/API outages?</div><div class="a">A228. Circuit breakers, retries with backoff, queued retries, partial completion state, and user-safe messaging.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q229. What is idempotency in GenAI actions?</div><div class="a">A229. Ensure repeated requests do not duplicate external side effects like tickets, payments, or updates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q230. What is anti-pattern in GenAI system design?</div><div class="a">A230. Letting an unconstrained agent write to production systems without validation and policy checks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q231. Why separate planning and execution models?</div><div class="a">A231. Planning can use stronger model occasionally while execution uses stable deterministic/tool layers.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q232. What is retry storm risk?</div><div class="a">A232. Uncontrolled retries during outages can amplify load and worsen incidents.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q233. How control retry storms?</div><div class="a">A233. Use jittered backoff, max retry caps, queue buffering, and circuit-breaker trip thresholds.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q234. What is the role of gateway in GenAI apps?</div><div class="a">A234. Centralized auth, quotas, logging, abuse control, and policy enforcement for all AI endpoints.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q235. How do you handle multilingual GenAI support?</div><div class="a">A235. Language detection, multilingual embeddings, locale-aware prompting, and localized evaluation sets.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q236. What is data freshness strategy in RAG?</div><div class="a">A236. Incremental indexing, source sync SLAs, freshness metadata, and stale-data warning logic.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q237. How do you monitor drift in production?</div><div class="a">A237. Track quality and retrieval KPIs over time and trigger re-evaluation on deviations.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q238. What is practical SLO set for GenAI services?</div><div class="a">A238. Availability, p95 latency, groundedness rate, tool success rate, and safety incident threshold.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q239. Why is business KPI linkage important?</div><div class="a">A239. It proves AI impact beyond model metrics, such as reduced resolution time or improved conversion.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q240. What is a complete production readiness checklist headline?</div><div class="a">A240. Security, evaluation, observability, reliability, governance, and rollback readiness.</div></div>

  <h2>20) High-Frequency HR/Managerial GenAI Questions (Q241-Q260)</h2>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q241. How do you explain GenAI to non-technical stakeholders?</div><div class="a">A241. It predicts likely next content from patterns and is strongest when grounded with trusted data and controls.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q242. What GenAI project did you deliver end-to-end?</div><div class="a">A242. Discuss problem, architecture, evaluation, safety controls, deployment, and measurable business outcome.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q243. How do you choose build vs buy for GenAI?</div><div class="a">A243. Compare time-to-value, compliance needs, customization depth, and long-term operating cost.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q244. How do you prioritize GenAI use cases?</div><div class="a">A244. Rank by business value, data readiness, risk, integration effort, and measurable ROI.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q245. How do you manage stakeholder expectations?</div><div class="a">A245. Set clear capability boundaries, pilot milestones, and objective quality/safety metrics.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q246. What is your strategy when GenAI output is wrong?</div><div class="a">A246. Detect via validation, recover via fallback/escalation, then fix root cause with data/prompt/model updates.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q247. How do you demonstrate ROI for GenAI?</div><div class="a">A247. Tie outputs to KPI deltas such as cycle-time reduction, deflection rate, or revenue-impact metrics.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q248. How do you build trust with users?</div><div class="a">A248. Provide citations, transparent limitations, consistent quality, and clear human escalation options.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q249. What are top failure modes you watch?</div><div class="a">A249. Hallucinations, unsafe outputs, tool misuse, retrieval misses, latency spikes, and cost blowouts.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q250. How do you scale a successful GenAI pilot?</div><div class="a">A250. Standardize platform components, governance, evaluation pipelines, and operational runbooks.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q251. How do you mentor teams new to GenAI?</div><div class="a">A251. Teach iterative experimentation, strong evaluation habits, and safety-first engineering patterns.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q252. What is your GenAI debugging approach?</div><div class="a">A252. Isolate layer-by-layer: prompt, retrieval, tool calls, model settings, and policy filters.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q253. How do you prevent vendor lock-in?</div><div class="a">A253. Abstract model/provider interfaces, keep portable prompts/tests, and separate domain logic from provider SDKs.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q254. How do you handle ambiguous user requests?</div><div class="a">A254. Ask clarifying questions, offer scoped options, and avoid high-risk assumptions.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q255. What communication skill matters most in GenAI roles?</div><div class="a">A255. Translating probabilistic AI behavior into clear risk/benefit trade-offs for business stakeholders.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q256. How do you run post-incident reviews for AI issues?</div><div class="a">A256. Build a timeline from traces, identify control failures, and implement prevention actions with owners.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q257. What is your view on AI replacing humans?</div><div class="a">A257. In enterprise settings, high-value pattern is augmentation with human oversight, not blind replacement.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q258. How do you prioritize responsible AI under delivery pressure?</div><div class="a">A258. Treat safety and compliance gates as non-negotiable release criteria.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q259. If given 30 days, what GenAI plan would you execute?</div><div class="a">A259. Baseline metrics, build MVP with guardrails, run evaluation, and launch controlled pilot with monitoring.</div></div>
  <div class="qa"><div class="q">Q260. Final interview close: what is your GenAI philosophy?</div><div class="a">A260. Ship useful AI fast, but only with measurable quality, strong controls, and operational accountability.</div></div>

</body>
</html>